## ⏳ Asynchronous JavaScript: Callbacks, Promises & Async/Await

JavaScript is **single-threaded** — it can only execute one thing at a time. Yet web apps fetch data, read files, and run timers without freezing the UI. This is possible because of the **asynchronous model**.

---

## 1️⃣ The Single-Threaded Event Loop

JavaScript has one call stack. When a JS function runs, it blocks everything else. But many operations (fetching data, timers) are handled by the **browser/Node.js APIs**, not JS itself. When they finish, their callbacks are queued in the **Event Queue** — waiting for the Call Stack to be empty.

```
Call Stack     Web APIs        Event Queue
─────────      ──────────      ────────────
main()    →    fetch('/api')   [callback when done]
              setTimeout()    [callback after 1s]
```

This is why setTimeout(fn, 0) still runs AFTER the current synchronous code.

---

## 2️⃣ Callbacks (The Original Way)

A **callback** is a function passed to another function to run when async work completes.

```javascript
function fetchData(url, callback) {
  setTimeout(() => {
    callback(null, { data: "response" })  // (error, result) convention
  }, 1000)
}

fetchData("/api/users", (err, data) => {
  if (err) return console.error(err)
  console.log(data)
})
```

**Callback Hell** — deeply nested callbacks become impossible to maintain:
```javascript
getUser(id, (user) => {
  getPosts(user.id, (posts) => {
    getComments(posts[0].id, (comments) => {
      // ... infinite nesting
    })
  })
})
```

---

## 3️⃣ Promises: A Better Way

A **Promise** represents a value that will be available in the future. It can be:
- **Pending**: Not resolved yet
- **Fulfilled**: Succeeded, `.then()` runs
- **Rejected**: Failed, `.catch()` runs

```javascript
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => {
    const success = true
    if (success) resolve("Data loaded!")
    else reject(new Error("Failed to load"))
  }, 1000)
})

promise
  .then(data => console.log(data))   // "Data loaded!"
  .catch(err => console.error(err))
  .finally(() => console.log("Done!")) // Always runs
```

---

## 4️⃣ Promise Chaining

Promises can be chained — each `.then()` returns a new promise:

```javascript
fetch("/api/user")
  .then(res => res.json())       // Parse JSON (returns another promise)
  .then(user => {
    return fetch(`/api/posts/${user.id}`)  // Nested fetch
  })
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(posts => console.log(posts))
  .catch(err => console.error(err))  // Catches ALL errors in the chain
```

---

## 5️⃣ Async/Await: The Modern Way

`async`/`await` is syntactic sugar over Promises. It makes async code read like synchronous code.

```javascript
async function loadUserData(userId) {
  try {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)  // Wait for response
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP error: ${res.status}`)
    const user = await res.json()                    // Wait for JSON parsing

    const postsRes = await fetch(`/api/posts?userId=${user.id}`)
    const posts = await postsRes.json()

    return { user, posts }
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to load:", error)
    throw error  // Re-throw if needed
  }
}

// Calling an async function
loadUserData(123)
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(err => console.error(err))

// Or in another async function:
const data = await loadUserData(123)
```

---

## 6️⃣ `Promise.all()` — Parallel Execution

Run multiple promises simultaneously, wait for all to finish:

```javascript
const [users, posts, products] = await Promise.all([
  fetch("/api/users").then(r => r.json()),
  fetch("/api/posts").then(r => r.json()),
  fetch("/api/products").then(r => r.json())
])
```

If ANY promise rejects, `Promise.all` immediately rejects.

---

## 7️⃣ `Promise.allSettled()`, `.race()`, `.any()`

```javascript
// allSettled — waits for ALL, even if some fail
const results = await Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3])
// results = [{status: "fulfilled", value: ...}, {status: "rejected", reason: ...}]

// race — resolves/rejects with whichever finishes FIRST
const fastest = await Promise.race([slowFetch, fastFetch])

// any — resolves with FIRST success (rejects only if ALL fail)
const first = await Promise.any([might_fail, might_fail, will_succeed])
```

---

## 8️⃣ The Fetch API

`fetch` returns a promise. Always check `res.ok`:

```javascript
const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    'Authorization': `Bearer ${token}`
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Mwero' })
})

if (!response.ok) {
  throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`)
}

const data = await response.json()
```

---

## 9️⃣ Error Handling Patterns

```javascript
// Pattern 1: try/catch (most common with async/await)
try {
  const data = await fetchData()
} catch (err) {
  handleError(err)
}

// Pattern 2: Catch at the call site
fetchData().catch(handleError)

// Pattern 3: Error return tuple (inspired by Go)
async function safeAwait(promise) {
  try {
    const data = await promise
    return [null, data]
  } catch (err) {
    return [err, null]
  }
}
const [err, data] = await safeAwait(fetchData())
```

---

## 🔟 Microtasks vs Macrotasks

Promises use **microtasks** (processed before the next macrotask). `setTimeout` uses **macrotasks**.

```javascript
console.log('Start')  // 1

setTimeout(() => console.log('Timeout'), 0)  // 4 (macrotask)

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('Promise 1'))  // 2 (microtask)
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('Promise 2'))  // 3 (microtask)

console.log('End')    // 2
// Output: Start → End → Promise 1 → Promise 2 → Timeout
```

---

## 💡 Summary

| Concept | Use When |
|---|---|
| Callbacks | Simple, one-time async (node.js fs, event listeners) |
| Promises | Chaining multiple async operations |
| Async/Await | Most readable, best default choice |
| `Promise.all` | Multiple independent requests in parallel |
| `Promise.allSettled` | Need all results even if some fail |
| `try/catch` | Error handling in async/await functions |
| `fetch` | Making HTTP requests from browser |
